ls ‘societies of control’, which deploy them in order to close down potential spaces of creativity and resistance. On the other, digital images take up the mantle of cinema, displacing habitual forms of cognition and forcing us to think in new ways. Deane-Freeman traces these dual impulses through the images of cinema, television and social media, as well as explicating key Deleuzian concepts, including virtuality, immanence and the outside.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDigital mediaxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079765740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978139951727040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781399517270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781399517270/original  a978-3-11-079765-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles